# Storybook Component Stories Rules

When creating or modifying Storybook story files (`*.stories.tsx`), follow these rules:

## Default Story (REQUIRED)

**CRITICAL**: Every story file MUST start with a `Default` story as the first exported story. This connects to Storybook's argTypes controls and allows users to interact with all component props.

```typescript
export default meta;
type Story = StoryObj<typeof ComponentName>;

// Default story (MUST be first)
export const Default: Story = {
  args: {
    // Component props here - these connect to argTypes controls
    label: "Example label",
    size: "md",
  },
  // Optional render function if component needs wrapper
};
```

**Rules:**

- Always named exactly `Default`
- Always the first story after `export default meta`
- Uses `args` property to define default props
- These args connect directly to Storybook's Controls panel
- May include `render` function if component requires wrapper or specific structure
- Should demonstrate the component in its most common/default state

## Component Props Documentation (REQUIRED)

**CRITICAL**: All component props MUST have JSDoc comments describing their purpose, type, and behavior. This documentation is used by Storybook to generate controls and documentation.

```typescript
/**
 * Props for the Button component
 */
export interface ButtonProps {
  /** The text or content to display inside the button */
  children: ReactNode;
  /** The color variant of the button. Controls the visual appearance and semantic meaning. */
  color?: "primary" | "secondary" | "tertiary";
  /** The size variant of the button. Affects padding, font size, and overall dimensions. */
  size?: "sm" | "md" | "lg" | "xl";
  /** Disables the button and shows a disabled state. Prevents user interaction. */
  isDisabled?: boolean;
  /** CSS class name for custom styling. Merged with component's default classes. */
  className?: string;
}
```

**Rules:**

- Document ALL props with JSDoc comments using `/** */` syntax
- Be descriptive - explain what the prop does, not just its type
- Mention default values when relevant (e.g., `/** Defaults to "md" */`)
- Explain behavior and side effects (e.g., "Prevents user interaction")
- Always export prop interfaces/types
- JSDoc comments must be directly above each prop in the interface
- Use complete sentences with proper punctuation

**Example of well-documented props:**

```typescript
export interface CheckboxProps {
  /** The label text displayed next to the checkbox */
  label?: ReactNode;
  /** Helper text displayed below the label. Provides additional context or instructions. */
  hint?: ReactNode;
  /** The size variant of the checkbox. Affects the checkbox size and text spacing. */
  size?: "sm" | "md";
  /** Whether the checkbox is checked by default (uncontrolled) */
  defaultSelected?: boolean;
  /** Whether the checkbox is disabled. Prevents interaction and applies disabled styling. */
  isDisabled?: boolean;
  /** Whether the checkbox is in an indeterminate state. Shows a dash instead of a checkmark. */
  isIndeterminate?: boolean;
}
```

## Story Descriptions (REQUIRED)

Every story (except Default) MUST include a description explaining what the story demonstrates and what it's implementing.

```typescript
export const Sizes: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Button size="sm">Small</Button>
            <Button size="md">Medium</Button>
            <Button size="lg">Large</Button>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button component supports four size variants: sm, md, lg, and xl. Each size affects padding, font size, and overall button dimensions.",
            },
        },
    },
};
```

**Rules:**

- Every story except `Default` must have a description
- Use `parameters.docs.description.story` to add the description
- Clear and concise explanation of what the story demonstrates
- Focus on what the story is implementing/showcasing
- Include key details about props, behaviors, or use cases
- Use complete sentences with proper punctuation
- Explain the purpose and when to use the variant/pattern shown

**Good description examples:**

```typescript
// ✅ Good - explains what and why
description: {
    story: "Button supports disabled and loading states. Disabled buttons cannot be interacted with, and loading buttons show a spinner animation while processing an action.",
}

// ✅ Good - explains the variants shown
description: {
    story: "Checkbox supports two size variants: sm (default) and md. The size affects both the checkbox itself and the spacing between the checkbox and label text.",
}

// ❌ Bad - too vague
description: {
    story: "Shows different sizes.",
}
```

## Grouping Variants (REQUIRED)

**CRITICAL**: Group related variants into single stories using `render` functions. Do NOT create separate stories for each variant. Each size, color, state, etc. should be a single story showing all variants together.

**✅ CORRECT - Grouped:**

```typescript
// Single story showing all sizes
export const Sizes: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Button size="sm">Small</Button>
            <Button size="md">Medium</Button>
            <Button size="lg">Large</Button>
            <Button size="xl">Extra Large</Button>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button component supports four size variants: sm, md, lg, and xl. Each size affects padding, font size, and overall button dimensions.",
            },
        },
    },
};

// Single story showing all states
export const States: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Button color="primary">Default</Button>
            <Button color="primary" isDisabled>Disabled</Button>
            <Button color="primary" isLoading>Loading</Button>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button supports disabled and loading states. Disabled buttons cannot be interacted with, and loading buttons show a spinner animation.",
            },
        },
    },
};
```

**❌ INCORRECT - Separate stories:**

```typescript
// DON'T create separate stories for each variant
export const Small: Story = { args: { size: "sm" } };
export const Medium: Story = { args: { size: "md" } };
export const Large: Story = { args: { size: "lg" } };
export const Disabled: Story = { args: { isDisabled: true } };
export const Loading: Story = { args: { isLoading: true } };
```

**What to group:**

- **Sizes** → Single "Sizes" story showing all size variants (sm, md, lg, xl, etc.)
- **Colors** → Single "Colors" story showing all color variants
- **States** → Single "States" story showing all state variants (default, disabled, loading, error, etc.)
- **Placements** → Single "Placements" story showing all placement options
- **Themes** → Single "Themes" story showing all theme variants
- **Variants** → Single "Variants" story if component has multiple variant types

**Grouping best practices:**

- Use flex containers to display variants side-by-side or in a grid
- Add visual separators or headings if showing many variants
- Keep related variants together (e.g., all sizes, all colors, all states)
- Use consistent spacing and layout

## Story File Structure

Every story file must follow this structure:

```typescript
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from "@storybook/react";
import { ComponentName } from "./component-name";

const meta: Meta<typeof ComponentName> = {
    title: "Base/Category/ComponentName",
    component: ComponentName,
    parameters: {
        layout: "centered",
        docs: {
            description: {
                component: "Brief description of what the component does and its primary use cases.",
            },
        },
    },
    tags: ["autodocs"],
};

export default meta;
type Story = StoryObj<typeof ComponentName>;

// Default story (REQUIRED - first, connects to argTypes)
export const Default: Story = {
    args: {
        // Default props that connect to Controls panel
        label: "Example",
        size: "md",
    },
};

// Grouped variant stories (each showing all variants together)
export const Sizes: Story = {
    render: () => (/* all sizes */),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Description of what this story demonstrates.",
            },
        },
    },
};

export const Colors: Story = {
    render: () => (/* all colors */),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Description of what this story demonstrates.",
            },
        },
    },
};

export const States: Story = {
    render: () => (/* all states */),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Description of what this story demonstrates.",
            },
        },
    },
};
```

## Naming Conventions

- **Story names**: PascalCase (e.g., `WithIcons`, `Sizes`, `States`, `Colors`)
- **File names**: kebab-case (e.g., `button.stories.tsx`, `checkbox.stories.tsx`)
- **Story names should be descriptive** and clearly indicate what's shown:
  - `Sizes` - shows all size variants
  - `Colors` - shows all color variants
  - `States` - shows all state variants
  - `WithIcons` - shows component with icons
  - `WithHint` - shows component with hint text
  - `AsLink` - shows component rendered as a link

## Complete Example

Here's a complete example following all rules:

```typescript
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from "@storybook/react";
import { Button } from "./button";

const meta: Meta<typeof Button> = {
    title: "Base/Buttons/Button",
    component: Button,
    parameters: {
        layout: "centered",
        docs: {
            description: {
                component: "A versatile button component that supports multiple color variants, sizes, and states. Can be used as a button or link element.",
            },
        },
    },
    tags: ["autodocs"],
};

export default meta;
type Story = StoryObj<typeof Button>;

// Default story - connects to Controls panel
export const Default: Story = {
    args: {
        color: "primary",
        size: "md",
        children: "Button",
    },
};

// All sizes grouped in one story
export const Sizes: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Button size="sm">Small</Button>
            <Button size="md">Medium</Button>
            <Button size="lg">Large</Button>
            <Button size="xl">Extra Large</Button>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button component supports four size variants: sm, md, lg, and xl. Each size affects padding, font size, and overall button dimensions.",
            },
        },
    },
};

// All colors grouped in one story
export const Colors: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex flex-col gap-6">
            <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
                <Button color="primary">Primary</Button>
                <Button color="secondary">Secondary</Button>
                <Button color="tertiary">Tertiary</Button>
            </div>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button component supports multiple color variants: primary, secondary, tertiary, and link styles. Each also has a destructive variant for dangerous actions.",
            },
        },
    },
};

// All states grouped in one story
export const States: Story = {
    render: () => (
        <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
            <Button color="primary">Default</Button>
            <Button color="primary" isDisabled>Disabled</Button>
            <Button color="primary" isLoading>Loading</Button>
        </div>
    ),
    parameters: {
        docs: {
            description: {
                story: "Button supports disabled and loading states. Disabled buttons cannot be interacted with, and loading buttons show a spinner animation.",
            },
        },
    },
};
```

## Checklist

Before completing a story file, verify:

- [ ] **Default story is present and first** - connects to argTypes controls
- [ ] **Default story uses `args`** - allows interactive control of all props
- [ ] **All component props have JSDoc comments** - every prop in the interface is documented
- [ ] **Prop interfaces are exported** - Storybook can generate controls
- [ ] **Related variants are grouped** - Sizes, Colors, States are single stories showing all variants
- [ ] **Every story (except Default) has a description** - explains what the story demonstrates
- [ ] **Descriptions are clear and informative** - explain what and why, not just what
- [ ] **No separate stories for individual variants** - group them instead
- [ ] **No linter errors** - code follows project standards
